text: About half a year ago, I think, when we were in the middle of expanding DeFi, we had heard a lot of the best opportunities were starting to move on-chain and centralized exchange trading was kind of hitting, diminishing returns, volumes were pretty low. And so we were like, okay, let's just spend more time looking at DeFi. And I think back then, RFQs were a bit of a fad. I think Doug from CrocSwap has written some interesting threads about this lately. I tend to agree with Doug. It's not a good design. And I think it's trying to take something that works in TradFi, but not really applying it well to DeFi. So I guess for context for listeners, RFQs stands for Request for Quotation, I believe. The idea is good. It's like, well, let's try to filter out this toxic flow that makers hate so much. Let's try to have retail interact directly with makers. So the retail will come in and say, hey, I'm retail. Give me a quote. And then the maker will say, hey, I'm retail. And then the maker will give them a quote, usually inside the BBO, or certainly for the size the retail wants, maybe better than if the retail were to hit the book directly. And then the retail gets the quote. And for DeFi, it's like a signed payload that you broadcast to some smart contract, which then verifies it. And then does the fund transfer between the retail and the market maker. It's just like OTC, but this protocol built around it, I guess. Yeah, this might sound good. And it happens a lot in TradFi. I think Exchange Street does a lot of this kind of stuff. And I think it's really good. You want to be on the side of retail flow, you're providing retail a great service by giving them bigger size and not getting front run by HFT. Good in theory, but in DeFi, it's just obviously a dumb idea because how do you prove that you're retail? Everything's anonymous and you're not KYC'd. And so as proof of concept for this, we basically just span up the simple Python script that just asks for quotes from these market makers. And they were quoting us five basis points away. Quotes were coming in. They were spelled for 60 seconds, 90 seconds or something. So most of the time it's pretty good for the market maker to get that fill, but they're quoting 100K in size or something like that. And we're just like, okay, we'll just wait until the price moves. And the price obviously moves. Crypto is really volatile. And when it moved, we were like, okay, we'll just like, rock, as this transaction, what are you going to do about it? And it seems super high sharp. We can do even better. You don't even have to wait until the price moves to trigger. It's basically a free option. And the option has time value. So you literally just wait until the options are about to expire. And then you just decide if you want to trade or not. So that makes it even more consistent than good. And so, I mean, we just did this and then I guess this is, we were not the first ones to do this, or maybe we were, but the market makers react and they say, okay, we're going to stop quoting you because you are making us lose money. And so you're clearly not retail. And they just start to give you super wide quotes. They're just not quoting at all. Then you just switch accounts. You just fund a new wallet and do it again. And fundamentally, I think there's just nothing wrong with that. I guess a little sort of a concern I have is like the main value we're adding when running this strategy is that we're showing the world we're proving that this RFQ microstructure is dumb. There should be like an intellectual reallocation of capital towards working on something that makes more sense. And maybe like we sort of accomplished that. I think now our views are like the makers have last look instead of the retail. I mean, like you said, we sort of like stopped running this strategy, but I think there has been an evolution. I do think that once you get into the market, you're like, okay, I'm going to do this. And then once you do that, though, there's like the whole benefit of RFQs like goes away. And then you can see the discussion on Twitter threads, but this is a hard problem to improve upon central limit order book. And I just don't think RFQs do it in DeFi. And I guess this was a good example of just us trying things in DeFi, just realizing how immature the space is and like how the protocols just like have not thought things through. And this was like a nice segue into like us basically deciding like, hey, maybe we're actually the best people to build something that is actually going to service retail and like create a platform for like decentralized price discovery.
